# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2010-united-states-census
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:2010-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:2010-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:2010-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:2010-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The **2010 United States census** was the 23rd United States census.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] National Census Day, the reference day used for the census, was April 1, 2010.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The census was taken via mail-in citizen self-reporting, with enumerators serving to spot-check randomly selected neighborhoods and communities.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] As part of a drive to increase the count's accuracy, 635,000 temporary enumerators were hired.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The population of the United States was counted as 308,745,538, a 9.7% increase from the 2000 United States census.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all states recorded a population of over 500,000 people as well as the first in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 200,000.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] It was the first census since 1930 that California did not record the largest population growth in absolute number.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Texas surpassed California's growth by 4.3 million to 3.4 million.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] As required by the United States Constitution, the U.S.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Census has been conducted every 10 years since 1790.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The 2000 U.S. census was the previous census completed.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Census is required by law of people living in the United States in Title 13 of the United States Code.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] On January 25, 2010, Census Bureau Director Robert Groves personally inaugurated the 2010 census enumeration by counting World War II veteran Clifton Jackson, a resident of Noorvik, Alaska.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] More than 120 million census forms were delivered by the U.S.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The number of forms mailed out or hand-delivered by the Census Bureau was approximately 134 million on April 1, 2010.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 census national mail participation rate was 74%.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] From April through July 2010, census takers visited households that did not return a form, an operation called "non-response follow-up" (NRFU).
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau delivered population information to the U.S. president for apportionment, and later in March 2011, complete redistricting data was delivered to states.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2082.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The Census Bureau did not use a long form for the 2010 census.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] In several previous censuses, one in six households received this long form, which asked for detailed social and economic information.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Were there any additional people staying here on April 1, 2010, that you did not include in Question 1?
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] What is Person 1's age and Person 1's date of birth?
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Is Person 1 of Hispanic, Latino, or Spanish origin?
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Does Person 1 sometimes live or stay somewhere else?
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The form included space to repeat some or all of these questions for up to twelve residents total.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] In contrast to the 2000 census, an Internet response option was not offered, nor was the form available for download.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Detailed socioeconomic information collected during past censuses will continue to be collected through the American Community Survey.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The survey provides data about communities in the United States on a 1-year or 3-year cycle, depending on the size of the community, rather than once every 10 years.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] A small percentage of the population on a rotating basis will receive the survey each year, and no household will receive it more than once every five years.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau announced that it would count same-sex married couples.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] However, the final form did not contain a separate "same-sex married couple" option.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] When noting the relationship between household members, same-sex couples who are married could mark their spouses as being "Husband or wife", the same response given by opposite-sex married couples.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] An "unmarried partner" option was available for couples (whether same-sex or opposite-sex) who were not married.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The Census 2010 Language Program was significantly expanded.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Language assistance in 49 languages in the 2000 Census was increased to 59 languages in Census 2000.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] In addition to English, Census questionnaire was available in five non-English languages: Spanish, Chinese (simplified), Korean, Vietnamese, and Russian.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 census cost $13 billion, approximately $42 per capita; by comparison, the 2010 census per-capita cost for China was about US$1 and for India was US$0.40.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Operational costs were $5.4 billion, significantly under the $7 billion budget.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] In December 2010 the Government Accountability Office (GAO) noted that the cost of conducting the census has approximately doubled each decade since 1970.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] In a detailed 2004 report to Congress, the GAO called on the Census Bureau to address cost and design issues, and at that time, had estimated the 2010 census cost to be $11 billion.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Locke credited the management practices of Census Bureau director Robert Groves, citing in particular the decision to buy additional advertising in locations where responses lagged, which improved the overall response rate.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The agency also has begun to rely more on questioning neighbors or other reliable third parties when a person could not be immediately reached at home, which reduced the cost of follow-up visits.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Census data for about 22% of U.S. households that did not reply by mail were based on such outside interviews, Groves said.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] In 2005, Lockheed Martin won a six-year, $500 million contract to capture and standardize data for the census.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The contract included systems, facilities, and staffing.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The final value of that contract was in excess of one billion dollars.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Information technology was about a quarter of the projected $11.3 billion cost of the decennial census.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The use of high-speed document scanning technology, such as ImageTrac scanners developed by IBML, helped Lockheed Martin complete the project on schedule and under budget.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Due to the rise in social media and cell-phone usage in the U.S., the Census Bureau used research gathered through a cell-phone study in order to target media and ads to populations that were nonrespondents and promote census participation.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] This study also helped gauge the mindset of those who fail to respond, trying to figure out why.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] This was the first census to use hand-held computing devices with GPS capability, although they were only used for the address canvassing operation.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Enumerators (information gatherers) that had operational problems with the device understandably made negative reports.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] During the 2009 Senate confirmation hearings for Robert Groves, President Obama's Census Director appointee, there was much mention of contracting problems but very little criticism of the units themselves.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The Census Bureau chose to conduct the primary operation, Non-Response Follow Up (NRFU), without using the handheld computing devices.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] There was a penalty of $100 for not completing some or all of the 2010 U.S.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau director Robert Grove, however, wrote "the Census Bureau has rarely prosecuted failure to respond.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] While the rationale for the mandatory nature of the census still applies today, our message for the 2010 Census is about the common good benefits of participation".
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The fine for non-participation is much lower than that for reporting false information.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now (ACORN) was given a contract to help publicize the importance of the census count and to encourage individuals to fill out their forms.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] In September 2009, after controversial undercover videos showing four ACORN staffers giving tax advice to a man and a woman posing as a prostitute, the bureau canceled ACORN's contract.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Various American celebrities, including Demi Lovato and Eva Longoria, were used in public service announcements targeting younger people to fill out census forms.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Wilmer Valderrama and Rosario Dawson have helped spread census awareness among young Hispanics, a historically low participating ethnicity in the U.S. census.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Rapper Ludacris also participated in efforts to spread awareness of the 2010 census.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The Census Bureau hired about 635,000 people to find those U.S. residents who had not returned their forms by mail; as of May 28, 2010, 113 census workers had been victims of crime while conducting the census.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Some political conservatives and libertarians questioned the validity of the questions and even encouraged people to refuse to answer questions for privacy and constitutional reasons.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] As a result, the Census Bureau undertook an unprecedented advertising campaign targeted at encouraging white political conservatives to fill out their forms, in the hope of avoiding an undercount of this group.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 U.S. census was the primary sponsor at NASCAR races in Atlanta, Bristol, and Martinsville, and sponsored the No.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] 16 Ford Fusion driven by Greg Biffle for part of the season, because of a marketing survey that indicated most NASCAR fans lean politically conservative.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] It also ran an advertisement during the 2010 Super Bowl, and hired singer Marie Osmond, who is thought to have many conservative fans, to publicize the census.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The results of the 2010 census determined the number of seats that each state received in the United States House of Representatives starting with the 2012 elections.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Consequently, this affected the number of votes each state had in the Electoral College for the 2012 presidential election.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Because of population changes, eighteen states had changes in their number of seats.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Eight states gained at least one seat, and ten states lost at least one seat.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The final result involved 12 seats being switched.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Some objected to the counting of persons who are in the United States illegally.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Senators David Vitter (R-LA) and Bob Bennett (R-UT) tried unsuccessfully to add questions on immigration status to the census form.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Organizations such as the Prison Policy Initiative argued that the census counts of incarcerated men and women as residents of prisons, rather than of their pre-incarceration addresses, skewed political clout and resulted in misleading demographic and population data.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Many residents of prisons counted on the 2010 census were those who identify as Black and Hispanic.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] This could lead to the loss of resources for underserved minority communities.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The term "Negro" was used in the questionnaire as one of the options for African Americans (Question 9.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Black, African Am., or Negro) as a choice to describe one's race.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau spokesman Jack Martin explained that "many older African-Americans identified themselves that way, and many still do.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Those who identify themselves as Negroes need to be included." The word was also used in the 2000 census, with over 56,000 people identifying themselves as "Negro".
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] In response to complaints over the word's inclusion on the 2010 census, the Census Bureau announced in 2013 that it would stop using "Negro" going forward, with the 2014 American Community Survey census form being the first without the word.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 census contained ten questions about age, gender, ethnicity, home ownership, and household relationships.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Six of the ten questions were to be answered for each individual in the household.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Federal law has provisions for fining those who refuse to complete the census form.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Detroit Mayor Dave Bing held a press conference on March 22, 2011, to announce that the city would challenge its census results.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The challenge, being led by the city's planning department, cited an inconsistency as an example showing a downtown census tract which lost only 60 housing units, but 1,400 people, implying that a downtown jail or dormitory was missed in canvassing.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] NYC Mayor Michael Bloomberg held a conference on March 27, 2011, to announce that the city would also challenge his city's census results, specifically the apparent undercounting in the boroughs of Queens and Brooklyn.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Bloomberg said that the numbers for Queens and Brooklyn, the two most populous boroughs, are implausible.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] According to the census, they grew by only 0.1% and 1.6%, respectively, while the other boroughs grew by between 3% and 5%.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] He also stated that the census showed improbably high numbers of vacant housing in vital neighborhoods such as Jackson Heights, Queens.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The District of Columbia announced in August 2011 that it would also challenge its census results.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The Mayor's Office claimed that the detailed information provided for 549 census blocks is "nonsensical", listing examples of census data that show housing units located in the middle of a street that does not actually exist.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] However, officials do not believe the city's total population will drastically change as a result of the challenge.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The state with the highest percentage rate of growth was Nevada, while the state with the largest population increase was Texas.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] Michigan, the 8th largest by population, was the only state to lose population (although Puerto Rico, a U.S. territory, lost population as well), and the District of Columbia saw its first gain since the 1950s.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] The resident populations listed below do not include people living overseas.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] For Congressional apportionment, the sum of a state's resident population and its population of military personnel and federal contractors living overseas (but not other citizens overseas, such as missionaries or expatriate workers) is used.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] These are core metropolitan rankings versus combined statistical areas.
[src:2010-united-states-census/2010-united-states-census] For full list with current data, go to metropolitan statistics.
